Author: mae_borowski

Message: The problem with characters like Sebastian is they only "change" for so long before the resort right back to their natural ways again. The reason Rick works so well as a main character is because his character has been honest from the start, he's never been something he wasn't "before" ... Michonne is another good example of what people end up resorting back "into" ... She was for a short time what she *needed* to be to get by until the Commonwealth offered her basically her old life back, and she grabbed onto it because deep down, she's been someone else, she "changed" for awhile, but we never saw her "before" persona ... We are now seeing it, and from the looks of it, a lot of people don't like this side of Michonne, but this is the REAL Michonne - I'm hoping she makes a choice and picks the persona we've all come to like, but this is the Walking Dead after all, nothing ever really goes how we'd like it too.So, yes, it'd be great if he "came around" and matured into a decent human being, but let's all be real, it wont last and he'll end up being a weak character. I just hope we don't see another development of 'Ruler Parent' gets killed, Ruler Parents' kid wants to now Rule in parents absence as they feel entitled to it ... That same old boring ass story.

Message: I don't think you get it. Rick and Michonne see the Commonwealth as the closest thing to society prior to the Walkers. They know that this place has its problems and said problems need to be fixed, but you don't throw away the baby with the bathwater. The problems don't need to be violently fixed with a revolution: they can be fixed through peaceful political means such as by leading by example, changing laws, establishing new precedents, and electing new representatives. Sure the Commonwealth is sorta a plutocracy at the moment, but with the right people and the right pushes it can become ideally what America was founded on (a republic for the greater good of the individual).Michonne caught herself and showed great remorse over her waitress-comment. She recognizes she has the potential to become a sociopath-elitist and she needs to keep herself in check better (thankfully her daughter will help her with that). Regarding the Commonwealth officers, they already got informally punished for it hence why the charges were pleaded to be dropped. Trust me, if they had a choice in the matter they probably would have preferred to serve a sentence rather than get the shit kicked out of them to the point they're clinging to their lives in the ICU. Making them serve a sentence after that would almost be like double-jeopardy as well as destabilize the military/police-force by making them feel their government doesn't have their back ever. This would further risk in achieving the Commonwealth's destruction - which is why Michonne defended them out of her principles. An ideal government needs to walk a balanced line: where it gets justice for the people in the right cases and justice for the force that supports it in the other right cases as well.

Message: I remember a while back Kirkman stated that he preferred to write for civilian characters as opposed to military, or other sensationally capable characters. At the time, he was absolutely right, but at this point in the story there are no civilian characters, and the only way I can see them being reasonably challenged is by introducing at least one group with members equal to or more capable than Abraham or Jesus for example. And whether he admits or is even aware of it, Rick's operated under the idea that he and his group are the last/best chance at rebuilding civilization. Ideally (for me) Commonwealth could have proven to him that there are people genuinely more qualified and better equipped than him to lead, a possibility that's been teased before, but a reality he's never actually faced. Sadly, unless Kirkman is willing to move Rick an itch away from his pedestal, I don't think the series has much more ground to cover.

Message: Well. considering that we're in a world that went utterly to hell with a great deal of people raping other people, the likelihood of attempted rape happening to both of them is pretty high. Hell, Carl, and Sophia were almost raped too. The only major characters that haven't are Rick and maybe Maggie, I can't remember for sure. It happens a lot in the Walking Dead.The point of this isn't a lack of creativity. They don't have similar experiences because the writer isn't creative, it's an intentional parallel between their lives thus far. The that they've both suffered and done terrible things to survive, and also done things in retaliation as well. The point is to show that they both get it, the things you can be pushed to do. It's to show us that they understand each other perfectly. Michonne's been looking for love for a a long time, but perhaps this is where her story is going. Finding fulfillment in familial love instead of romantic.

Message: Let me start by saying I dig the direction overall here. I know a conflict had to brew at some point, but I hope this isn't going to be the big one, but just a false start that gets resolved to show these people are alright, before something bigger rears its head. It's just that after thinking about it for a minute, why would they even need a coup? Mercer has all the military power and security. If he doesn't like how his men are being treated and used, with how people are specialized into jobs in this society, can't they just go on strike? No security til you stop treating us like shit and wasting us on meaningless jobs like babysitting? I doubt it would take long for people to give in.I guess it depends what kind of "governer" she is. Like if they've established term-lengths or anything like that. If she's just leading with the intent to lead til she dies, I can see that breeding resentment as it clearly has with Rick and Maggie multiple times. If they put a time limit and actually vote on new leaders periodically, then uprisings would be less likely as they could just wait it out til they can get voted in.In fact, I'm surprised we've only seen groups with singular leaders. I would think something like a leading council, a small group of people leading with equal vote and power that get cycled out periodically. I realize that's what was in the latest walking dead telltale game and it didn't work out for the best...but I feel like it'd work better if psychos and assholes weren't allowed on the council. Whatever, just musing and rambling at this point.

Author: axedroam

Message: The show has its ups and downs yes, but let's stop arbitrarily pretending the comics were always better. Tired of these annoying purist who keep saying that shit just because. If you've been following the books since the beginning, you can see at this point just how many things the show actually did better.So if anything, the show just compliments the books now.Yes some things I do prefer still in the comics, but 100 episodes later, it's fair to say they started to match each other in pros and cons that I sometimes can't decide which one is ultimately superior. They can be enjoyed and appreciated for different, and the same reasons.AMC didn't make a perfect show, but Kirkman didn't write a perfect comic. The "comic is always better" attitude is hackneyed at this point.

Message: I get what you're saying, but at the same time this is still a story and it's disappointing when a story arc like the Whisperers end in such a boring way. Imagine how lame it would be if Rick had just formed a blockade and waited for Negan and the Saviors to starve to death, or if the Governor had gotten sick and died. Obviously, those aren't exactly one to one comparisons to Beta, who still went out with a fight, but I still think that Kirkman could've chosen a better way to end Beta's story, that could still remain realistic. I mean, look at Game of Thrones, a story built on being as realistic as they can in a fictional world. A lot of characters in Game of Thrones don't die in a blaze of glory, but they are still good because they are done so well, and Beta's just isn't. Sorry for my tangent, I was just really hoping for a cool death for Beta and got really disappointed.

Message: I'm having kind of mixed feelings about this arc. Firstly I don't think the whisperer's war-strategy is actually that efficient as the comic wants to portray it. The fact they're not using guns (probably because of lack of guns) means their stabby-stabby ways don't differ that much from a regular zombie, and when you start thinking about it, it's kind of retarded to assume people would let any zombie to a stab distance just because "it's zombie". Sure, they were able to wreak havoc but that's not because they are a worthy opponent but apparently because the good guy militia was somewhat incompetent. A whisperer is pretty much just a shit upgrade from your average zombie and the fact the soldiers weren't able to repel them yet is kind of unbelievable.Second complain would be how I'm a bit disappointed in the direction the arc took. I was hoping the tension in the arc would be caused by a more complex set of moral and ethic dilemmas on the topic if it's "just" to declare a war on people because they have a differing culture. I really liked the fact for example rape-habits seemed in many occasions be the deal breaker and many people considered they had to re-educate the people to be "civilized" again, which even has many historical real world parallels. But apparently we're going at this with the old fashioned kill them all type of a way now, aren't we? I think it's kind of a downgrade in the storytelling department.

Message: While I understand letting him live is not the kind of emotional payback people were expecting (even though you could argue that life in prison could be worse than death for him), you have to understand the context. It's not about your average movie cliches or even being morally consistent, I think the writers were aware that the "mercy" is all over the place even as you pointed out, but they're using him to showcase their world can change to something where killing for revenge and self-satisfaction isn't necessary. Him surviving the ordeal without getting executed is a signpost of humanity finally starting to climb out of the rotting mud hole they've been knee-deep this entire comic. In a way it's a very pretty conclusion to the arc.

Message: I'm seeing so much argument about "show is better" or "comic is better, grow up fanboy!!"But let's be realistic, most of the characters in the comic have no real character outside of what their task is.Up until issue 98 when they revealed Maggie was pregnant all Glenn ever was in the comic was the guy who got supplies, screwed Maggie, and pretended to be Sophia's Dad. That was it. Let's be honest with ourselves. I've been binge reading these comics all week and it's only taken me a couple of days to get to this point, and that's all Glenn was. Kirkman slid in the Maggie being pregnant thing at the last second to try to make Glenn's death more tragic.That's why I didn't even care when they killed Abraham in the comic. He was just muscle who screwed Rosita and then Holly. That was all he was. The show, he was fleshed out a little better and I at least thought "well that sucked" when they killed him off.There are some things the comic does better, like Woodbury and Andrea. But let's not lie to ourselves and pretend that everything is better than the tv show. Because each has weak areas and there are some things the show gets better than the comic and vice versa.

Message: There's a gay couple in the comic, and you know why it's no big deal at all? Because his sexuality isn't the only thing about Aaron that the writer wants you to focus on. In Marvel Comics lately when they replace classic characters with a black/gay/Muslim/etc. character, those characters are 1-dimensional and their race or sexual orientation is the big focus of them that the writers and Marvel wants you to focus on. Like Miles Morales. They piggybacked him off the name and recognition of the Spider-man character, and he easily wins his fight, most of the time with literally one touch. Everyone instantly loves him and the only real conflict is all artificial. The same with Female Thor. Miles' race and Female Thor's gender is all the writers of those books want you to focus on. They don't want to write them to be more than that, they just want to pat themselves on the back for getting rid of "CIS-white Male" characters from the books.Aaron is gay, but that's not the defining thing about his character. He's a guy who goes outside the wall, along with his boyfriend, and they risk their lives to look for good people that they can offer sanctuary to. They saved the lives of Rick and his group by bringing them to Alexandria.That is the defining thing about Aaron, the kind of man he is. He's selfless and his main goal is to help good people get to safety. His resolve falters in this issue, but at least he has good reasons for why he thinks maybe they should stop looking for people.If characters are introduced that are gay or black or whatever, the writers of said comic need to stop making that the only thing you are to focus on. Marvel and DC are horrible about that. Aaron and Eric's characters are more than just their orientation, and that is why they are good characters.And is anyone else wishing that Abraham said "Mother Dick" in the comic like he did on the show?

Message: I respect Lori for coming clean. I think Rick will be more understanding than most would think. Sure, Lori stepped out of her marriage but I don't think she is a bad person or a whore. Take a look at the circumstances. Rick was in a coma for who knows how long. The fact that Rick woke up unharmed and made it to Atlanta is a miracle, he should be dead. Then there was a nationwide epidemic. Shane didn't have to but decided to make sure Lori and Carl made it out of their small town in one piece and brought them to Atlanta. I'm sure the whole experience was very traumatic for both of them. I think Lori was in a very stressful situation and sought comfort from a friend. I do not condone it but I certainly wouldn't fault her for it given the crazy circumstances. Why does everyone blame Lori and not Shane? He had ill intentions from the beginning and he took advantage of a very vulnerable woman.

By doing what is best for everyone Rick has stumbled across two negative effects; the first being, from the perception of the group, he has too much power, and the second being inoder to do what's right he has had to give up his humanity, he has become 'the walking dead'.I don't think the rest of the group is ready to give up on hope yet, preserving their way of life is just as important as their individual survival. Rick no longer agrees, he now cares more for making it to the next day then about how he does it.
Author: disqus_t7jtaWKop9

Message: Agreed but to a point. The crux of Rick's mindset (at present) and the one that everyone's been getting into a twist over is that the world they knew is gone. The structures in place to keep order, obliterated. The thin veneer of culture that held fast the selfish impulses of the masses, torn apart.Hope is the thing that keeps all these people going but its the hope that the world they knew will someday return that keeps their minds shackled.And that, plus the stress of the existential threat of zombie-hood, is not helping matters. The bitterest pill to swallow is that their ideas of right and wrong (by virtue of their past lives) will kill them in a lawless land where anyone with a gun can become king... if only for a time.

Message: I'm going to be honest, I'm totally with Tyrese in this one. Yes, he is a totall hypocrite, I'll admit to that, and he was wrong to accuse Rick of being a murder when he is just as guilty of the same crime, but Rick was wrong from the beggining.His logic that Tyrese is the reason that Carol tried to kill herself, though on the outside is correct, does not take into account that Carol would have had to have been suverly suffering inorder to do something like that. I mean, she had a daughter for Christ's sake, if she was ready to give her up over losing Tyrese then there had to have been much more going on outside of Tyrese's control.Obviously Tyrese was wrong to cheat on Carol, but if Rick wants to be a 'leader' he can't go around looking for fights, and that is exactly what he did. I think the issue was attempting to show the fragile minds of the group (namely that of Rick and Carol's, and Tyrese to some extent), but the pattern that I am starting to see is Rick becoming less concerned with the good of the group and more concerned with his own version of justice.Rick is like a vigilante, dealing out justice by his own codes in a way he sees fit. With each issue he takes more and more control over the group, and this fight between him and Tyrese was not about Tyrese's afair, but instead about him fighting back against the way Rick has begun to assume all power. And from that standpoint, I have to side with Tyrese, despite his hypocracy.

Message: Another year (like the I2 version of year five), would've been good to set up plot points and build up to the game. This made a good ending to an arc, but not a good ending to the series. Here are some things I would have included:-Damian Wayne Nightwing turning himself in for his hand in Ra's crimes, talks to Cyborg in jail-Reverse flash teaming up with Gorilla Grodd-Catwoman going undercover in the society -Cheetah, Bane, Firestorm, and other absent characters being in the story-Batgirl's death (I love the character but she's been in two runs of the comic and hasn't done anything important in the games)-Black Lightning gets incapacitated (but not killed) so he can't help stop Braniac -Aqualad becomes Black Manta-Address what is going on with Vixen and Jason Todd, that was a pretty built up to reveal and it amounted to very little -More stuff with the regime and SupergirlWhat would you guys want to see if there was another year of the series?
Author: ofccoleblack

Message: There is still the upcoming Annual that was announced, and I think it's supposed to focus on Bruce meeting up with the Kents and is supposed to be "family" focused. So if we see Damian go back to jail, that would probably be the best place for it to happen. Maybe he fled Gorilla City in the chaos and went back home, then Bruce just tosses him in jail.We did see Cheetah briefly. She joined forces with Ra's, but I don't think she's done anything outside of stand around and look menacing. I guess she's just sticking around and helping whoever just so she can get a shot at Wonder Woman.Then Black Lightning shouldn't need too much of an explanation. He is the President now, I figured he's probably busy organizing a response to Brainiac's invasion and keeping his daughters safe, and doesn't have the time to get physically involved. Steel, on the other hand, might need more of a reason. Also, what happened to Plastic Man and his son? Last time we saw them they were all melty, but I doubt that killed them. Also I'd guess Starfire is either recovering from her injuries taken in the fight with the Red Lanterns, or she's out trying to find Connor and Cassie.Hopefully they do a retelling of the game's story after the Annual comes out and some of these things are covered in the first issues (like did Grodd throw Scarecrow in the Lazarus Pit, and that's why he's back?). I assume they'll also do another series bridging the gap between IJ2 and IJ3 whenever that comes out. The Black Manta/Aqualad, Jason Todd, Vixen stuff can be done there, since they don't actually appear in the game's story. I'd guess they're just issues dealt with after Brainiac was taken care of.I'd also like Enchantress to get involved in something. She's the only DLC character that hasn't been brought up in this story, and Zatanna has been absent for so long. I don't think Raven was ever captured when the Regime fell, maybe Zatanna is just on a magical mission hunting her down?

She's guilty, she knows and that guilt will haunt her forever. But that's also what drives her to do good.Through forgiveness and compassion, good came out of evil. That's what marks the base of Injustice's moral message and the main difference in the worldviews here. If Green Arrow didn't get her away back in Year One, Superman would have killed her and all the good she's done ever since wouldn't have happened. Depending on how one sees Ground Zero's canon status, that may have meant the failure of the Insurgence and the Regime expanding over the multiverse.I do agree the comic lost the subtlety in the latest issues, though.

Get out, kill a kid then start melting polar ice caps? He should have prioritised Batman for the first kill, but he probably did not know who is the real danger here. Then just get out of there, hide and soak up solar energy. In the end, he is just used for a simple "remove another character that is not in the game" BS move without any real addition to the main plot, except that Batman has now seen Amazo.As I said, I don't care much about Tim as a Robin, Dick is the first, Jason is the tragic one and Damian is the blood son, so Tim is the happy one? And I will admit, Damian is my favourite one, but not Injustice Damian, the main DC story one. The Injustice one comes across as a whiny brat, not unlike Kylo Ren (hate him too). That said, I don't care about Tim as Robin, but his death was pointless. Use him as a skin for Robin in the game, not just kill him off for no reason.As for the wildcat thing. I don't know that character and If I had not read in the comments that he might have more lives to use, I would say Batman finally lost it, but taking that into consideration... let's see where it takes us.

Message: A little something I notices after I watched the Flash today. Zoom in Injustice 2 said that he can not go home anymore cause the Regime killed one of his ancestors so his timeline does not exist anymore as it did when he left for the 21st century.That said, IF his future/present does not exist  anymore the way it did when he left, does that not imply someone somewhere altered the time line? I mean Zoom is a time traveller. Would he not have known about Metropolis getting nuked and the Regime getting formed. Clearly he did not know those things, let alone that he can't exist anymore cause the Regime killed one of his ancestors.My point is this: If we analyse what Zoom said and take into context, does that not mean someones somewhere altered the time line at some point? We don't know where, but it has to be in the 5 years of the Regime being around. Either at the beginning of Metropolis getting nuked or up to Injustice 1 game story. Would that then also not imply that they just created (the writers) a back door for a plot in Injustice 3 for the reason of this alteration?Is the person responsible for this the one giving the Joker the nuke (we still don't know where he got it from)? Or did this person tell the Joker about Superman's identity (how else would he have known about him and Lois then)?Am I just looking too much into this or what? Your thoughts?
Author: sux_to_be_u

Message: Well Fate is asked by Cyborg why he let Metropolis get blown up, and he says something about letting Fate take its course. I think the Lords of Order conspired for something like the Regime to happen, but Kent Nelson was against it and they didn't plan on Batman successfully resisting Superman's takeover for so long or him calling in help from another world. Certainly Superman went too far for the heroes not to oppose him on principle, but the Regime did bring a lot of benefits to Earth that were lost when it fell. And since the Lords of Order have often been portrayed as caring more about the universe itself than any of the people in the universe that definitely sounds like something they would do.Alternatively, it wasn't fated to happen and the rise of the Regime was supported by the Lords because they wanted a balancing of the scales and Order to succeed in place of Chaos at any cost.Nelson also said he changed fate for the Insurgency too many times and now Nabu won't let him oppose the Lords' agenda anymore. Which is bad news for Earth because the Lords ended up saying, "Oh, fuck this shit!" and supporting Brainiac's arrival because Earth being destroyed would allow the universe to be re-ordered somehow. Saying any more would be spoilers for the game, but it's pretty heavy stuff to say the least.

Message: Okay, why is Zod so damn silent? In the source comics he loves to talk, although the best writers know how to make him not sound too much like a Bond Villain. It makes sense for the Eradicators not to talk much because they're robots, but he's not at least gloating about how easy humans are to kill? Fail!Also, hold on, did Green Arrow just say he KILLED a Kryptonian? And he was totally willing to do so AGAIN? And nobody saw fit to comment on the fact he JUST SAID THAT? What, what, WHAT?! You can't just bring that up and then not expand on it, or have everyone present act like it's nothing! Fail!Oh God, Harley's back involved with the plot and she just saved Jonathan's life. I should have known Martha's dismissal of her was too good to last. Please don't turn into the Kents forgiving her, please don't turn into the Kents forgiving her, please don't turn into the Kents forgiving her... Oh, who am I kidding? That's just what they're going for, isn't it? EPIC FAIL!Batman, I won't blame you if you kill Zod - I'd be a gigantic hypocrite if I did, seeing as he totally murdered your son right in front of you - but if you do, you lose any right to keep waving your no-killing rule in everyone's faces as a sign of moral superiority. Between this and you using weed-killer on Poison Ivy, you've already lost the right to act like it's a big statement of morality given the myriad things you can demonstrably do to a person and still say, "I didn't kill them." So I'm watching you closely, and you best consider your next actions carefully.Jesus this issue is a joke. And I was really looking forward to it, too. I was fully ready to declare it the worst issue of Injustice 2 so far... but then I considered it and thought, "Is it really that bad, compared to the verminous, soul-tainting badness of Injustice 2 Issue #7?" So I guess it's just the second-worst issue in the series, if only because #7 is a Harley-centric issue that blatantly displays everything wrong with her character in this continuity, taunts us with her plot armour and tries desperately to make her sympathetic by dragging in her "wacky" daughter who's the worst interpretation of the snarky-little-girl trope I've seen in my life despite her crimes arguably making her irredeemable. Only a complete hack would be able to top that.

Message: The rise of the Regime was rooted in many things - chief among them, situations that vindicated Superman's arguments that certain people are beyond saving and should be dealt with appropriately as such. It was maintained for so long not just because Superman and associates were all-powerful, but also because there were benefits to being ruled by a guy who can't be hurt by mortal weapons, including putting an end to crime and war, creating a prison that unlike Arkham and Stryker's could actually hold the people incarcerated there and ending humanity's reliance on fossil fuels by advancing the cause of green energy by decades using Luthor's genius and Kryptonian technology, among other things. And they didn't start out as brutal dictators; they became that way over the course of a long and bitter war as Batman and friends continued to force their hands and they in turn came up with increasingly extreme responses.So you can't say that no rational human would ever believe they were right. For a while they were, and then they became wrong. It's far more nuanced than you make it sound.

Message: I agree with you that what Injustice Superman and his side did was wrong, but you have to admit the world really was better held together compared to ours today under his dictatorship. If you were a regular American citizen in the world, you would probably not complain at all in Injuistce Superman's world at all. It has been said that under Injustice Superman's rule, there are no large conflicts in the world (can you even imagine a world without wars?), the planet was more advanced economically and technologically, he singlehandedly stopped an planetary invasion from Apokolips (year 1), made sure no threats comes from outside of earth (year 3), got rid of beings like the gods and trigon that meddles in human affairs (years 3 & 4), and there have been overall global peace. Small crimes still exist but are largely covered by superheroes. There is still the Superman vs Batman conflict, but normal citizens of the world are not harmed or involved at all. Again, Superman's regime is wrong and built on ill-means, but if you're a normal man living a normal life it would not affect you at all, and you would live a safer life. If you still argue the world overall was worse under Injustice Superman's rule, you are dead wrong.

Message: (Sorry in advance for the long ass comment. I got way too carried away XD)The thing is, morally THE END RESULT DOESN'T MATTER.I'll give you a real world example; You could argue that, thanks to companies offshoring we have many things that, otherwise, we probably wouldn't have. Because offshoring makes making products cheaper to the company, so they can produce more, and since it's cheaper to make it's cheaper to sell, so more people will may be able to buy those things, which ultimately will give the company more benefits (so they can expand and investigate better stuff). Also, the fact that the products have a lower quality (and lifespan) now makes it so the companies are force to innovate more, which also helps the end result we end up having. That's why we have such wonderfull phones nowadays, for example.But those things come with many costs. "Blue collar" jobs are at their lowest in the western countries thanks to offshoring, we get products that last less and less every year and the countries the companies "offshore" to are usually third world countries that don't get too benefit by them moving their production lines there. The main reason why anyone will offshore their company is because there's less bussiness regulations so they are able to pay misseries to their workes while, at the same time, making them work way more hours than any western country will allow them to.But nobody gives a fuck about offshoring being horrible because you can have a expensive phone that allows you to watch YouTube videos while taking a shit. Or cheap new pretty clothes every season. Or whatever the fuck you want. And that's a good thing, isn't it? (and don't get me wrong, I'm part of the problem, I care way less than I should about the world's problems)We ("we" as in "humanity") would have ended up having those very same things but more slowly if offshore wasn't a thing. And the same goes for wars, peace, human rights etc... We will get there. The world is a better place (in term of violence, human rights, poberty rate etc) than it was ever before in human history. And sure, we're not going to accomplish World Peace tomorrow or in 100 years. But I like to think that we will eventually get there.And not only that, when we get there, it will be so much more important because WE did it. Because WE accomplished that. Superman system would have eventually failed because he would have, eventually, died. Wether it was because someone killed him or he died naturally, he would have died, and after that humanity would have gone back to killing each other because the only reason why they weren't doing that is because "daddy was looking".It's the same thing that happens with kids. If you teach a kid that "he shouldn't do that because you will punish him" he's not going to learn why not to do something, the only thing he's going to learn is "not to do shit in front of you". On the other hand, if he understand why doing something is wrong (other than "because if I do that I'll get punished") he'll probably won't do it again.

Message: There is no better prison though. There can never be. All the best prisons invented in comics fail for a simple reason: they are not bound by laws of physics or logic (just like super powers). They are at the whim of a writer. You could say they invented an adamantium prison inside a black hole placed inside the phantom zone guarded by krypton tech and guarded by an army of daxamites, and still the Joker, or any other criminal, would get out. Because they are the antagonists and they are needed for the story to continue.This could be worked out by introducing new villains and let the old ones rot in jail to be forgotten, but this has never been  thing. Even the Punisher, known for killing every criminal, always lets the known names escape when they confront him. This is why every hero has a gallery of rogues and the forgettable one off villains who vanish after the deed.The whole 'why didn't Batman do X to prevent Z from happening since he is so smart?' is a dumb thing to say. Batman is fictional. Why didn't he do it? Because the writer of the story didn't decide to write it. The writer is not Batman, is not a super smart polymath, hes a normal person who happens to write comics. More importantly the only utopias we see where crime is solved and problems are taken care of are the hipothetical futures that heroes find when they travel in time, where things are neat and ordered. An utopia would be a boring thing (not really though, there are some particularly good comics about people with powers fighting 'normal' crime alongside other people with powers who lead their lives aided by the powers instead of putting on spandex.

Message: I'd like to clear a few things up here. A) Batman wasn't sloppy in choosing who to bring. In the end, it was all Batgirl's decision. She gave permission to bring Blue Beetle along and in the end, she was the one who told him to stay back and help if there was anything wrong. B) There was something wrong. If you're on a stealth mission and you're told that you're only there to break them out if things go awry, then as soon as something is wrong, you break out the big guns. Beetle is completely justified in his actions. The results were just collateral damage and as long as intent isn't there and there was no knowledge of any sort of underground area where animals would die, I think he can be forgiven. He did his job correctly. C) That species was going to die anyway! If there was literally only one of that species left, then it was going to die alone later on. You could say that they have cells to clone it, but if that's the case, then doesn't that mean that the species can be revived either way? It obviously would need differences in the DNA in order to repopulate, so if their plan hinged on repopulation, then they must have a method to change the DNA and not just clone the same one over and over. D) Does Ra's have a point in his goals? Sure. Were his methods justifiable and intelligent? Not at all! I question what went through his head. "Hm, how about I kidnap their children and use them as leverage against them to join my side! That's worked so well for me in the past!" *Insert sarcastic comment about being an idiot here* It's never worked for him before. He always gets his ass kicked when he kidnaps anyone from Batman's life. And given how a majority of his friends are less intelligent and more impulsive, he should know they'd come after him!E) Did Beetle screw up with El Diablo? Maybe? I don't know how, since every other time someone has been blasted with that weapon, it's only ever been concussive on the first shot. And I don't remember Diablo being Captain Adam or Firestorm when it came to the whole explosion thing, so I feel as though the writers may have messed up more than anyone else in this scenario.

Message: Okay, I'm a big fan of Injustice Harley but even I shake my head at the constant omission of her involvement with Metropolis, like with Steel's line here. She should get way more shit thrown at her by certain characters. I don't say "they should have thrown her to jail/executed her hurr-durr", there could be meaningful interactions and character development all around if they just spent a few more panels on this, or even an issue. The dialogue with Ra's a bit earlier was something like that, but that's not really enough. The game proper does a better job at this (Supes holding onto that grudge, some shit talk in intros, a rabid WW actually guts her etc.)There are viable reasons why heroes personally affected by Metropolis might leave her alone (she has more use helping around than being a deadweight in prison, the attack would have taken place even without her help, hero XY rising above their own grief/anger and giving the benefit of the doubt to a criminal, yadda yadda). Batman especially, who could push some justification of his crime fighting methods by pointing at her, maybe trying to counter the guilt he feels about the Joker and others. Meanwhile there should be people still set out for revenge, definitely, not just the Regime folks. Missing stuff like that just leads to inconsistencies and readers getting hate boners. There's great story potential here without disrupting the status quo, and while I love Tom Taylor's take on things, I really don't see why he's not using it. Oh well, the series ain't over yet.

Message: I think you've missed the point.Batman hates taking help from other heroes. Comics history is full of him bitching that he didn't need [insert superhero here]'s help or that Gotham City is "his turf". And because he doesn't have the guts to privately contain or just kill the monsters, sociopaths and psychos he ran into on a regular basis his only port of call is to hand them over to the authorities despite a track record that says the authorities just can't handle them.Arkham Asylum is a worthless, piece of crap facility. I know it and so do you. It can't reform its inmates, it can't contain its inmates and if we had a facility that was half as crap at its job in Real Life, we'd have shut it down long ago and replaced it with one that works, which is what Superman ended up doing in the first prequel comic. Batman wouldn't even have to kill them, just find a way to get them locked up somewhere they couldn't escape from every other Tuesday.Batman's choice not to properly deal with the Joker was wrong. You don't believe me, look what he did to Lois Lane and Metropolis. Because he's such a lone wolf who insists on doing things his way, the responsibility for what these animals do when their handlers let go of the leash inevitably falls on him. Animal Man didn't kill the Arkham crazies before now because he's been doing his thing looking out for the Animal Kingdom, that's his jurisdiction. Most others didn't do it because until Metropolis they had all mostly underestimated the ability of supervillains to threaten the world. After Metropolis all their illusions were shattered. And still, you could see it in his eyes that even after the Joker killed his best friend's wife and child (by which I of course mean tricked said best friend into killing them) and contrived it so that would lead to a city of 11 million or so (the comic's words not mine), not to mention that he was going to be the godfather of said child, Batman was still going to try to stop him the useless law-abiding way.All he had to do, really, was admit to himself that his way of doing things wasn't working and somehow adjust it. He didn't, and this is the result. Or perhaps you'd like to ask any of the Joker's victims, or those of any other Rogues Gallery member, what they think of Batman's no-kill rule?

Message: The way I see it is this for all who say Batman is not to blame:1. First off, I agree with all those that say it was the governments fault. In so many US states there is a death penalty. After X amount of tries to 'heal' Joker and failed, they should have done something different. Some are just beyond help.2. In a way it is Batman's fault. He created the Joker when he took the law into his own hands. He broke the law and hunted criminals when that is clearly the job of cops at that time he was not yet deputized by Gordon I think, so he was breaking the law. And he got off it with no punishment for nearly killing someone and creating the Joker. Superman never created Darkside or Lex Luthor. Superman went too far, but Batman did not go far enough, unless it was to stop Supes. He never allied with a demon to stop Joker. He never put Joker into permanent sleep state In the game, Yet he kidnapped and kept his former allies in a off the grid holding facility with no hearings or a lawyer, just like Superman. He was no better than Supes. Damian said: You don't kill but are OK with brain trauma. Why not paralyze the Joker or cause a permanent coma. That is not death. Oh yeah, that would be going too far. As if dressing as a bat and taking the law into your own hands is not going too far.3.  He never consoled Superman, helped him after the attack (or even Dick and Damian for that matter, Batman is an emotional cripple, Superman became just like that, then tried to implement Batman's logic to put fear into people so they don't do stupid things and Bats disagreed with it, even when it is HIS tactic). If Batman had sided with Superman, he could have steered him from becoming the way he did, countering Wonder woman. But he didn't, so Wonder woman told Superman he was right and pushed him further. No one to be his consciousness. And isn't that Batman's thing?4.  Batman knew what the Joker wanted. To push him to do something he never would do. Like killing him. But he never considered as the great detective he was, that the Joker might change tactics? A massive fail on Batman's side. Besides, it is still not known where he got the nuke from.5.  Batman said how many Superman killed. OK, granted the people he burned, Alfred, Billy and GA. But Captain Atom was in a way self defense, since the captain did get the order to kill Superman. And The Martian is the same thing. We don't know if he intended to kill Diana or just incapacitate her, but he was the one to draw first blood, Superman just countered him. As for the Parademons Superman killed. So what? They aren't conscious, they are Darksides mindless killers. Is Batman crying for every Braniac drone he 'killed'?6.  Both made mistakes. Superman: Allying with Sinestro, forcing everyone to fall in line, Accepting the Specters help, killing Billy (really don't like he did that) and many others. Batman: Trusted Constatine, trusted Ares,  did nothing when Zeus tried to take over the world, trusted Hawkman....they both messed up.7.  Batman's logic in my view is faulty when it comes to the Joker. Or in general. Yes he cleaned crime with dirty cops, the mafia and small time thugs. But he created directly or indirectly super villains, and they are much worse than a simple mob boss. GJ Bats. Either Batman is lying to himself or he is as crazy as the people he sends to Arkham. The lying option: He knows Arkham is useless, all the super villains that he sends there never get cured based on the track record. They just bide their time to escape again. And Batman is looking the other way instead of fixing a broken system. The insane option: He thinks that doing the same thing over and over again, this being to capture the bad guy, send him or her to rehabilitation and wait for them to escape will one day yield a different result. So far it hasn't. Only more deaths of innocent people. And what is the textbox definition of insanity? Doing the same thing over and over again in the hopes of getting a different result.8. I the comics Ganthet said that Krypton destroyed itself and that is why the Lanterns did not help. OK, continuity fail, since in Injustice 2 we clearly see Brainiac destroying Krypton. Is that not an outside threat to which the Guardians have to act upon? Or is Ganthet full of shit?Conclusion: Superman didn't see that he was becoming what he hated. A tyrant. The path to hell is paved with good intentions. But Batman is no better. He is not the solution he hopes to be, just the other side of the problem. I mean Supes killed around a 1000 people and god knows how many Parademons. But the Joker? In the game it was 11 million! And yet, Batman defended Quinn, who is an accomplice to mass murder! How fucked up is that. Yes she reformed, but if Hitler reformed, do you think any sane person would still not want to shoot the guy?Batman is for absolute freedom, Superman for absolute order. Order keeps you safe but limits your freedom, like a dictatorship. So who would want to live a life so restricted, right? No matter how safe you are. On the other hand freedom can never be absolute. Even in democracies we have limitations and the police and judged to enforce those limits. But the question is this: If order keeps you safe but not worth living since you are not free, freedom gives you allot of freedom and choices. And unfortunately, some will abuse those freedoms to commit crime. So how good is freedom, if your too dead to enjoy it because someone robbed you and killed you? The best path is always the one in the middle.In every discussion I see people praise Batman and hate Supes. I say everyone is at fault, just to a different degree. As I said, Superman went too far, Batman not far enough, when it could have made a difference. If Batman believed that this would not change Superman, did he look in the mirror lately? It took 2 bullets to forever change him. Supes lost FAR more than Batman ever did. And Batman was not a friend to help him, when he again could have made a difference.I would still like to know the reason that drove Diana to become like she is in this story. I usually like WW. Bats is the pessimist, Supes the optimist but she is the realist. Here she is just a bitch.Sorry for the long post.
Author: sux_to_be_u

Message: Nice post but I disagree with most of it. Sorry.Superman did create some of his own villains, with over fifty years on scene it is kinda inevitable. Like Livewire and Parasite.Batman could not have joined Superman. That would be condoning his action and he would be in no better position to stop him. He had to choose between having whole Justice League on a slippery slope or split it between them and keep at least some of them without guilt by association like The Flash has to deal with now.As for cleaning dirty cops and corruption and crime... Batman did not succeed in that and he knows it. He cannot succeed on his own he need the system to wake up and be proactive. How to do that now that Gotham became dependent on him as he is on her, that is the question.He can prepare for many things, but the best thing about him is that he is human. He will make mistakes and no man can be prepared for absolutely everything. I would not like him at all if he was a Marry Sue. So I am not about to blame him for not expecting Joker to have Superman kill his family and nuke his city. Their Villains did switch targets before and they always handled them in the end. So they may be blamed for complacency, but... That seems like a cheap shot to me. Not being confident after having their statistics in battle and crime solving would be strange.In closing I am a Batman fan but I enjoy classic Superman. For me the preference comes from ordinary man who decides to do extraordinary thing because he can, and he thinks it might help. I enjoy that more than the near omnipotent being who is at core so good that he is incorruptible and is not faking it. Which is whole premise of Injustice that he did become corrupted by his power once he started using it without any self imposed restriction. And it is same thing that Bruce Wayne himself said many times that he knows it would happen even to him if he ever killed someone.I agree with you about Wonder Woman, I hope there is more to the story than jealous woman sensing her opportunity once her crush's wife died.
Author: matejsojka

Message: Like your way of thinking, but let me poke some holes in it.First off, I don't know that much about Villain histories for the most part, so I apologise for the Superman not making his own bad guys mistake. But do any of his core villains meet that criteria?Yes, Superman had no more self restraint. Because he believed that his restraints before lost him Lois, so he doesn't care anymore, right?As for Batman, I guess, just like with Supes, it depends on the version we are talking about. In Kindom Come, that Supes suffered at the hands of Joker as well and he went into exile, not over the top. On the other hand in the Dark knight trilogy movies, Bruce at first did want to kill Joe Chill, he was just beaten to it.And speaking of Bats. OK, he doesn't kill. Does he take responsibilities for failing people? The families members who lost loved ones he couldn't save cause he breaks the law as a vigilante, but doesn't kill because reasons? Even cops kill when in self defence or to protect the people. I'm not saying he should execute someone in cold blood, but in the heat of the moment when he has to save a hostage or stop a bomber? He will not kill the bad guy to save the innocent? SWAT does that and they are authorised law enforcers. If he doesn't kill because he is not a law enforcer, well he shot himself in the foot there.Why this bothers me is because of this: In many version where a core DC character went bad, in many cases it was Superman. And yet in the Crime syndicate universe it was Batman's opposite, Owl man who was the real threat, at least in the animated movie.As for your ordinary man thing... Batman is Bruce Wayne, he was never ordinary to begin with. Ozymandias was rich, gave it away and got even richer. All I'm saying: Bruce is a great detective, fighter, infiltrator... etc. But is he a good business man or is that Fox at work? Did Bruce earn his wealth or just inherit it?That is the only extraordinary thing about him. He's rich and can buy all the gadgets, have access to the best tech and not worry about his daily job, family or social life. Same as Tony Stark. Take all of that away, Bruce is still a great fighter and detective, but the Joker would not take him seriously by calling him Bruce.As if they handle Batman with kid gloves but decide to shit on any other character if it sells the comic.Anyway, nice chatting with you and exchanging ideas.

Message: Man, fuck Animal Man. "Sure we killed a whole lot of people, and we kidnapped and threatened children. And yeah, we resurrected and then threatened to RE-kill Alfred. But it's all okay, because we're saving these animals who actually have zero chance of successfully rebuilding their populations because there's only two of them and despite what the Bible might tell you THAT IS NOT ENOUGH TO REBUILD A POPULATION!!!!" I may have added a bit to it but that seems to be the gist of his speech.Also, I still REALLY hate this stupid idea that Batman not killing Joker makes HIM responsible for everything that Joker then does. Hear this all the time, and it's always stupid. If a doctor performs lifesaving surgery on someone who then goes on to commit a crime, is the doctor responsible for that? If a cop arrests a criminal who then gets out and goes and kills someone, is that cop responsible for the death? What if a random person pulls a kid out of the street before being hit by a car, and that kid grows up to become a mass murdering psychopath, is that random person then responsible for all those deaths? Batman captures criminals. He brings them in, then lets the justice system deal with them. That is his job. It's the same thing that pretty much every other hero does. If Joker escapes from prison, that's on the Prison. Not Batman. If Joker kills a dozen people, that's on Joker. Not batman. When Joker WAS sentenced to death, Batman didn't stop him from being executed. He let it happen, because that is what the justice system decided was his due punishment for his crimes.

They were both too extreme, only they were far opposite extremes. One too soft, the other too violent.It doesn't have to be that one is right and the other one is wrong. Just because you don't agree with one doesn't mean you have to agree with another.Only people who could possibly "support" the Regime after reading the story up to this point are edgy kids or have a really warped and twisted view of how things actually work.

Message: Tom Taylor, who cherry picks his characters and disregards important character traits all the time (and get a free pass because the injustice universe is his universe), usually is a hit or miss as a writter. I personally think he has gotten better, and more well-versed with the DC universe recently. But he stills falls short. He fails to present moral conflicts in a meaningfull, unbiased way. And that's ok, no writter is obliged to know so. He could very well make a simple, yet entertaining series without feeling the need to prove people wrong about how shallow he is.The events of the games ended up aligning with whatever he writes, because it's his jobn to build a thrilling, yet vague, story about how things develop from the fact of a cynical, ruthless world. I like it, but at the same time, I despise the fact that some people think this is top quality work.Eh, just internet personal opinions in the end.

Message: Even though I still think Starro works better as JLA villain, I'm actually enjoying this plot involving him and the red lanterns. In fact, I think some elements of this Green Lantern arc could be use in a Green Lantern movie. It could work like this:The movie would be a mix of "space adventure" and "buddy cop film" and would showcase the beginning of Hal and Sinestro partnership, as the two go on a mission (against the guardians orders) to find out who killed one of the green lanterns. After some investigation they would find out about the red lanterns existence. When they came to the red lanterns planet, Ysmault, Hal and Sinestro would save one of the villains prisioner, Saint Waker, who would reveal their Red Lanterns backstory and their plan to use Starro (he would be a ancient alien conquerer who was ressuected and infected by the power of rage) to destroy the guardians and "purify" their universe with the power of rage. After that moment, the trio would be captured by Atrocitus, and Hal would be possesed by one of Starro's star. However, thanks to Ganthet last invention, Saint Walker is choose by the ring of hope, becoming the Blue Lantern, and Hal, using his own will power, breaks fre from Starro's control. The three lanterns are able to escape in time to warn the guardians and so the movie finnaly comes to it's climax: A big, epic space battle between the Green Lantern Corps (plus Saint Walker) and the Red Lantern Corps (plus Starro).

Message: Let me show you how the movie should be done and you're very welcome in advance.We open with a human waking up.. he's on a planet that's destroyed... however, he finds that he can breathe and live... and as he looks up... he sees a dead battery. Close in on his eyes and we see a reflection that starts to glow green.We cut back to a spaceship, one of Ferris Space Exploration's premier fleet ships (similar to Cloverfield Paradox); where Abin Sur crashes into the vessel. In the panic, Hal and John Stewart (the military leader) try to lead the team to find out if he's hostile, but he's wounded. As a peace seems to be brokered, BOOM... in comes the Manhunters. As they fight, humans are caught in the crosshairs. However, Abin tries to shield them, resulting in his death. The ring comes to Hal, and in a big green explosion he destroys them but passes out.He wakes back up to the first scene. Suddenly, he's attacked by Thaal Sinestro, the last remaining Lantern. He explains that the Manhunters were hunting them and actually slaughtered most of the galaxy's Lanterns, and the Guardians. It turns out the Manhunters were the Guardians' first decommissioned police squad, re-activated and driven by a new hack. With the genocide of most of the Lanterns, the batter basically lost its life.Sinestro explains that this is why the Oan battery is dead but their rings do somewhat work on sheer willpower. He takes Hal to a refuge camp on Korugar with the remaining Lanterns, including Tomar-Re, Kilowog and his daughter, Soranik.The Manhunters, now controlled by a cloaked master, track them there and attack once more. The Greens are outnumbered but saved by the final 2 remaining Guardians Syed and Ganthet. They reveal they've been scouring the galaxy, taking them to the Source Wall, to find a way to reactivate the Lantern. There, a mystical source (hinted to be Metron) taught them about the full range of the emotional spectrum, and the Blackest Night prophecy, which they interpret to be the Manhunters.They do however find out there's a way to kickstart the batter so the rings can go find new Corps-men; that's by capturing the Ion entity the initial Guardians used to build the battery -- Metron had the location of the entity. Together they all go after Ion and eventually get the battery started again. However at that point, Syed kills Ganthet turns out to be the traitor...He was the one who wanted the Manhunters back into play because he felt they were a stronger Corps. However, his plan would need the battery restarted aka Ion so that's why he played his peers... with this repowered battery, he could now build more Manhunters. In the final battle, Soranik is killed driving Sinestro off the edge. He too gets badly wounded but Hal eventually saves the day by absorbing Ion. Syed is imprisoned, and the battery restarted as a force of good.Rings go out across the galaxy now.Sinestro renounces the Green and goes off... exploring the prophecy and finding the Book of the Black. Here, is where he's inspired to form his Yellow Corps to do protect the galaxy his own way.Syed taunts Hal in prison, telling him he needed a reborn Manhunter army for what's to come... and we glimpse Atrocitus on Ysmault.Finally, we see green rings coming to sector 2814, with one going to John who's rehabbing after the attack on the spaceship which opened the movie.CreditsPost-creds:We see the cloaked figure who corrupted the Manhunters and revamped them. Shockingly, it's not Syed, who's imprisoned, but turns out to be Desaad. This ties back into JL and Steppenwolf's war on them. Desaad corrupted Syed and used the anti-life equation on the Manhunters
Author: disqus_qlYVaWwIcm

Message: Man, so many observations to make.1. Oh, wonderful (and I say that sincerely), some prominent lines and characterisation for Talia and her daughter. Wonder how Ra's convinced him to join him. But what can Steel do about it now? He's probably making his getaway by this point. I'm sure hoping they don't let that string dangle.3. Wouldn't want to be Blue Beetle right now. Knowing your earnest attempts to help your friends have only made things infinitely worse is bad for a growing superhero's self-esteem, especially when you accidentally kill a guy and a bunch of endangered species. 4. So, King Solovar is in on Ra's' big scheme and working with Gorilla Grodd, despite usually being a good guy and him and Grodd usually being sworn enemies. Interesting... 5. Speaking of whom, I was wondering when Grodd was going to show up. I wonder how this comic will tie into his formation of the Society, as well as his alliance with Brainiac. Either way I don't expect him to be too loyal an ally to either Solovar or Ra's.6. A re-imagining of Dr. Ivo and Amazo, as well, with a family-threatening extortion similar to the one the League was using on Kirk Langstrom in the Son of Batman movie. I suppose stranger things have happened in this universe, like Lex Luthor being a good guy.

Message: Listen, Superman may be the bad guy here, and he may have done all those things you mentioned, but that doesn't mean he's wrong. Batman's seeing the worst in him goes all the way back to the first issues of the prequel comic.* The Joker tricks Superman into killing his fucking family and blowing up Metropolis for no reason other than that it was an easy win over Superman, so Superman does what we were all waiting for *somebody* to do and guts the bastard. Batman and a bunch of other people treat this like he murdered a good guy even though none of them have been in the same position and killing the Joker is more of a public service than a crime. * Tired of hearing news reports about wars and disasters that no one else seems able to stop, Superman goes to Bialya, dethroning the local dictator, then makes a public call for the governments of the world to stop fighting each other or risk his intervention. Batman chews him out for scaring people, and has no answer when Superman points out that what he's doing is just Batman's modus operandi on a global scale. * Aquaman sends troops to sea ports around the world and issues an ultimatum to the land-dwellers: stay the hell out of the ocean, OR ELSE. Superman gives Aquaman a taste of his own medicine by lifting Atlantis out of the water and placing it in a desert. The merpeople are all shook up, but the only thing permanently damaged is Aquaman's pride. Batman somehow finds a way to treat this unpleasant but defensible action as a dick move. * Superman gets fed up with the revolving-door prison that is Arkham Asylum and plans to move its inmates to a more secure facility. One would think Bats would be happy to be eased of his burden or at least try to negotiate something with Supes, but no. His exact reasons for opposing Superman are never given, but his overall demeanour is that of a child having his toys taken away - not very flattering. * Confronted with the grim knowledge that an Apokolips invasion plays by different rules than your average supervillain battle, Superman kills Kalibak and his invading army of parademons, putting a stop to the slaughter and saving the world. Civilians all over the world cheer his name to show their thanks, but Batman treats it like he crossed the moral event horizon, even though Superman's actions saved the burgeoning Insurgency as well. It is at least gratifying to see Huntress call him out for being an ungrateful bastard. * Martian Manhunter, having spied on the Justice League while disguised as Hawkgirl for a week, reads Wonder Woman's mind and, seeing how violent and bellicose she's become, decides to kill her. Superman saves Wonder Woman with heat vision, accounting for Manhunter's tumble into the ocean and the SHOCKING REVEAL in the game proper that he was disguised as an Atlantean chronicler and why he was mostly out of the main storyline. Batman, not content with having lied to his allies about their reasons for capturing Hawkgirl, decides to frame this in such a way that it looks like a dick move from Supes, though what exactly he wanted Superman to do instead, I'm sure I don't know.All those things are morally gray, and Superman himself felt pretty bad about a number of them, but each can be defended as a grim but necessary act, one that Batman either didn't or didn't want to see. In fact, an argument can be made that Bats' paranoia is the cause of a lot of the conflict between him and Supes, because he got the chance to join Superman's efforts and declined. If there's a barrier between them, it's one both of them played a part in erecting, and when Supes talks about Batman always seeing the worst in him, I reckon he's talking about all those things as much as everything else.

Message: I guess you have a point. But Batman knew that humanity would rather die on its feet than live on it's knees. Superman cannot be judge, jury, and executioner. Same flaw as capital punishment - you risk killing innocent people. And Batman has ALWAYS tried to ensure that his rogues gallery gets psychiatric help. Honestly, if they'd stay put long enough or leave their doctors alive long enough for a psychiatric evaluation to be completed and sent to the authorities, then several of them probably WOULD get the death penalty, as they are aware of what they did and take pride in it. And you're right, it isn't as though Batman hasn't considered killing the Joker before. Hell, he's TRIED before, after the death of Jason Todd and in Batman: Hush. The first time he was stopped by(ironically) Superman, and by the fact that the Joker had been made the UN ambassador of some middle eastern country. In Hush, Harvey Dent(who had made a deal with Hush: Hush cured him of Two-Face, and Harvey agreed to stay away from the game Hush was playing with Batman) called Commissioner Gordon to the scene in time for Gordon to stop Batman from killing the Joker. Batman was stunned by Gordon's attempt, as he had assumed that after the events of The Killing Joke Gordon of all people would understand.

Message: I think that's a good thing. For a character whose selling point is supposed to be that he's human and doesn't have any special powers, he's often been written as invincible, undefeatable, and just overall a Gary Stu. I prefer the stories where his humanity is kept in check. People complain that Superman is too powerful and Batman is more relatable, but Superman seems more vulnerable and human nowadays than Batman does. Even Batman once referred to him as "the most human of us all." I often find it hard to relate to Batman, but that's why I like the writing of Scott Snyder and stories like these. They remind us that he is just a man underneath that cowl, even if symbolically, he's much more. Physically, he still has limits and he can be beaten. He even says it himself. We shouldn't lose sight of that.

Message: Well, this arc was overall disappointing. Don't get it wrong, the writer has the potential to write great stuff. But...between the conveniences (one example : dumbifying Bane), questionable decisions (one example : letting Bane there ? really ? are you stupid too ?), bad red herring (a good one is coherent ; one example of incoherent : Batman saying "no" while being alone at a place where no one sees/hears him to pretend there's betrayal), telling/narrate obvious stuff (one example : his letter to Selina), a mixed usage of repetition (used it badly in one issue and used it well in the next one), lost routes (one example : the letters led to nowhere, they just served as an alternative to recitative, however, the core difference is recitative doesn't have to lead anywhere, thus it'd have been better to keep it as such or, if letters is really the thing, to integrate them physically at one point), unrisked plot elements (one example : Catwoman's betrayal being fake), pretty words not equaling depth (be it in dialogues or letters ; not always, but it happened regularly), and while we're upon words "coolness" being cringeworthy (one example : it's not impossible, it's Batman 8D ; it'd work far better in comedy), reducing a character to emphasis, cheapily, romance (one example : Catwoman being the only one to understand the desire to dress up), there's more than one thing to progress on writing wise.

Message: I get that the side by side comparison of Bruce and Bane is to illustrate the differences in how the two came up.But honestly, I think the material is weak and lazily portrayed.Bane is not a villain trifled with because of the aura of fear he projects, he is the perfect combination of menacing and shrewd.His methods are like the Bat's which is intimidation through fear.In the previous issue his methods were strategic to psychologically taunt the Bat, in this issue his behavior is vulnerable and out of character.Bane has been relegated to the stereotypical villain who finds it important to rant about his superiority. This is the attribute of the insecure and conveys the opposite. It seems as though he is frustrated. He should be forcing the Bat into a corner, so that he makes wrong decisions. Instead its the standard "I'm better than you" routine normally reserved for villains of lower import it simply isn't Banes style.The fight was lack luster we already know Batman is going to recover because he is giving Bane free punches, when the scene with Catwoman shows up it is all but certain. Any excitement for the next issue is killed because that is just going to be a wrap up of this dull uneventful fight.

Message: I AM SUICIDE. I AM BANE. I AM CAT. Find a new catchphrase and way to tie up your baddies. At least Selina would not be so... conformist... as to copy others. And she did not see how the birds were hang up in Batcave.Also she was shown being beaten up and bruised and here she is right as rain.When did Barbara meet Duke? That panel where Batman tells the current lineup they are his strenght makes no sense. When he told them to get out of city it was without Barbara and without Kate. And if he said it before, it would be either with Tim in it or without Duke and Kate. Also Cassandra is missing from that picture.The whole parallels they are drawing between Bane and Batman are making me uncomfortable. I would never call Bruce Wayne sane person. Good person, yes. Capable person, yes. But not sane. However he is functional. His whole notion that he can control himself and everything and everyone around him and thus solve every problem without killing is crazy and it is only because he is driven by that insanity that he succeeded so far. But here they show him to be Batshit crazy mamma's boy and I find that cheep and creepy. He was always portrayed as being intense, but quiet and here he talks to his mother out loud his whole life. Am I only one who finds it out of character? Remember when in Year One story he asked his father for a sign and a bat flew trough a window? He did not speak out loud.Only thing Bane and Batman have in common is that they are both self-made superhuman. But that is where it ends. Batman did it trough diligence, preparation and obsession, Bane trough anger, hopelessness and addiction. Batman thinks people should get a break in life from those who inflict pain on others, Bane thinks all should go trough hell to show they deserve to live.Also Bane is out of character, he was shown to abhor his mother's weakness that she shown by not being able to survive in prison and he wanted to find his own father so he could kill him for leaving him there and escaping himself. All he ever care about was himself and his prowess and his venom.Every Batman villain is something. They were created to reflect the evils faced by people in urban environment. Even Bane. If you did not figure it out, he is addiction.If we find out in next issues that Batman was letting Bane beat the crap out of him I am gonna be pissed. There is no sensible reason to do that. If Batman beats Bane before entering the Asylum it ends there, especially if he has Catwoman to free captives. If he fights and loses he would still buy time for both Alfred and Selina. Batman may be crazy but he is not stupid.

Author: matejsojka

Message: "Batman using Inmates to do his fighting? .... Out of character behavior for him......them locked up in their cells.....Not on corridors talking to Bane and possibly getting killed or recruited."I agree, Batman's strategy here does not make any sense, I wonder if it's the writer's plan to go get us worked up about it. If so the plot so far seems ludicrous and he better have a hell of an answer.If I were to hazard a guess this is just an over-exaggeration  to make Bane seem formidable as an opponent. This is done poorly with ridiculous confrontations with the other villains. An entire issue is thus wasted on cheesy male bravado.Putting that aside some things in this issue if isolated from the plot are interesting character depictions. These are entirely my opinions."Scarecrow being scared of Bane."Scarecrow is perpetually scared despite exhibiting very good cognitive responses in the face of crippling fear. This is an interesting quirk to show, because it alludes to the abuse he has gone through. His inability to feel afraid anymore, motivated him to delve deeper and study it. Like most scientists that value their work above all else, he has grown committed to his field of study. When people like Bane or Batman confront the Scarecrow he reacts subconsciously in fear.Batman and Bane have a reputation, they both are intimidating  and they can be equally unpredictable. To a normal person these are enough to warrant the fear of them. Scarecrow is far from normal, he has lost the ability to know that he is scared."since when does Solomon Grundy fear anything?"I don't see why Grundy can't feel fear. His mental state is not capable of making him piece together his innate superiority over Bane. But fear is primal to every organism that has the ability to fight or flee (to defend themselves).

Message: Am I the only one who is really disappointed with this arc? It was a great concept but we've seen nothing of the actual war, a lot of the villains characterizations seem OOC esp given where this event happens in the N52/Rebirth timeline, and these jokes and riddles are so uncreative that any of us could find them given a 5 second google search.I generally like King's work, but to me this arc feels like he had the idea of Bats and Cats finally getting together - and then separately decided to do Jokes and Riddles story to be political (which is fine) - but then either he or DC wanted them combined to build suspense for the arc over the whole summer. It worked, more people are buying Batgirl, Birds of Prey, etc trying to get some clues as to what Selina's answer will be. But in turn, I feel like both stories (the proposal/engagement and Jokes/Riddles) were diminished in the name of a big marketing push. Just my two cents, and still looking forward to the finale, but yeah I think it could've been executed much better.
Author: disqus_vjHejdrypL

Author: avaspeaks

Message: I'm well aware of where this takes place on the TL, which I pointed out already, and I've complained on other issues about the lack of continuity for this arc. This arc just actually doesn't make a ton of sense.Joker has lost the ability to laugh after one year of batman? Riddler talks about murdering the whole bat-family at dinner with Bruce, but the next issue is teaming up with him against the Joker? Deadshot/Deathstroke are the greatest assassins in the DCU, but somehow waste hundreds of rounds and kill dozens of innocents? When Deadshot lost his family to stray bullets and is sworn to never kill a bystander?None of it fits. So the only logical explanation is that King had a couple big things he wanted to do, (Bat/Cat, Jokes/Riddles, fleshing out of Kite Man) and then tried to stitch them altogether into one story. The end result is a lame mash up of things that don't make sense, and disappointment at how his cool ideas were not executed properly. I think people have been giving King a bit of a free pass on this for the good arcs earlier in his run (I am Gotham, I am Bane). But you gotta call a spade a spade: This story had limitless potential and has squandered it all so far.

King making him appear more like a random thug that uses riddles as an excuse to be able to call himself a supervillain; all for the sake of "cool" and "dark", very different from Zero Year or the last few years of New Earth), a Joker that doesn't laugh, Bruce wanting to marry Selina, using Joker's past in the Killing Joke as an Easter egg and then turning it into an argument how it's just one version of multiple options and he's actually full of shit (this is more of a fact, yes, but the whole "reference" was so obvious it felt like one of those fanfictions that has no idea how to write a character so they copy lines and concepts from other official stories to validate themselves), the whole conflict between two villains mixed in with a some sort of No Man's Land, some sort of Injustice-villain-version (even though it makes way more little sense here) and now they're bringing up Joker's fear of being forgotten from the Arkhamverse and Joker's Last Laugh under a form of a joke meant for him to kill that guy because "dark and edgy", ripping any sort of meaning from it. That's not creepy, that's just stupid. (What about it is supposed to be humanizing Joker again? What about this entire arc is supposed to humanize anybody at all? I just see cardboard copies of the real characters. It's just being superficial, going from a refference to another. Is this the point? To send a nod to all those things happening in the past for new readers? Are they poking us to go read pre-New52?) At least Kite-Man is more than a joke, even if we could have seen this turn of events from a mile, but still...So comic, please decide what you want to express already. I understand the intent, but oh my god, that execution is unforgivable; I'm still not sure when I'm supposed to laugh and where I'm supposed to be involved. Maybe it makes sense though? I mean, Joker in his whole identity crisis doesn't seem to know how he's supposed to react either 8D Maybe we, as the audience, are supposed to empathize or something. lol But then he'd be the one narrating and not Bruce, so I guess that explanation throws itself out the window. I tried.

Message: While I adore to bits the issue as whole, I fear the "I found you" from Selina means that Annual story or even just that version of her first time in Batcave is cannon now. My other problem here is that Superman is not that easily recognized as Clark Kent. Clark has different posture, mannerisms, tone of voice, slightly over-sized clothes to hide the muscle tone, even different facial features to a degree, since Superman keeps some facial muscles clenched. It is not just glasses and hairstyle. Yes, each of those things are small and would not fool anyone, but all of them together paint completely different character. So someone like Selina who is not familiar with both Clark and Kal-El should not be able to figure it out so easily. Daily Planet Staffers, however, have no excuse for being dunces.I like the Clark / Bruce dynamic, but I do think that Gordon is his closest friend. They do not reveal Batman's identity by choice, not because lack of trust.I love the art here. Both Selina and Lois look fantastic. And they act like wives that care, instead of wives that nag. And that handshake while men just stand there killed me.Bruce and Clark describing each other is so sweet. Justice League movie had awesome scene where Bruce talks about Superman like this, it is great to see it from both of them. Though given Superman was taking his wife into potentially dangerous environment, how come he was not listening?
