To be a villain in gotham, you pretty much have to be a mix of super genius and superhuman.Penguin hires pretty much russian mercenaries, is a master of judo, his umbrella is full of tricks, etc.Scarecrow is a genius chemist, is a master of kung fu which he mixes with ballroom dancing to create a style that fully benefits his long limbs, and yeah the fear gas he creates.Joker is a genius who is also a hard sociopath who can change personalities on a whim to even throw off the smartest people out there, he doesn't feel pain, is a weapons and unarmed fighting expert or master, is heavily unpredictable, has a lot of trick weapons, has underlings who are loyal to him + harley who is superhuman as well, and he is faster than peak human in speed.etc (and those are just weaker batman villains)Maxie Zeus (a c villain) does stuff like drop a ceiling on batman that he has to hold up while he releases a damn lion to come eat at him while he's busy holding up the 1000 pound ceiling (that represents the atlas holding up the sky/uranus)Another c villain (or maybe b) The Mad Hatter is able to hang with batman somewhat in unarmed combat, is particularly quick, and has a hat that can mind control people.People who can't fist fight their way out of a swat team without any stealth involved is overall unable to function as a main villain on gotham unless they are part of a bigger picture like the falcones and maronis (who also have hit hard times) and even they have some pretty stand out combatants in the form of falcones ripped daughter and holiday (albeit he went against his father falcone)In the end, that kid would have to become super intelligent, do borderline batman training, have charisma and money to draw people to him, and also have impressive tech or trickery to do well or at best he might be an underling boss to someone and not like harley or echo.

Message: Theory:After reading this issue, I started to realize that all flashbacks are from two different timelines of the DC universe: The Pre-crisis timeline and the Post-crisis timeline. This, plus the fact that, during King's run, both Batman and Catwoman don't remeber correctly when they first meet, made me thinking: What if this flashbacks are not just tributes and fan-service, but also consequences of Doctor Manhattan actions in the DC universe?Just like happened in "Superman Reborn", (where Superman and Lois, after remembered each other, their love and their son, were able to fuse both their pre-crisis and new 52 timeline into a new one), since Batman and Catwoman got even more close, to the point they are getting married, this might be causing their old memories to return as well. However, instead of these memories been from their true past, they are regaining memories from two different eras: The goofy and colorfull tone from the silver age and the dark and serious tone from the modern comics.I think that, whatever is going to happen in the upcoming Booster Gold arc, it will fuse both eras into one single timeline. which could serve as metaphor for DC Rebirth message, that comic books don't need to be always dark and serious. Comic books can also be goofy and colorful. In the case of Batman, even though  most his stories are usually dark and have serious themes (Ex: Long Hallowen, Killing Joke...), they can also be fun and, in certain level, goofy and colorful(Ex: Laughing Fish,  The riddle-less robberies of the riddler, Love Bird, or even some Batman TAS episodes like Joker Millions and Almost got 'Im).

Message: Thank you!!! Imo there are two reasons Batman doesn't kill the Joker and it is NOT HIS MORAL CODE! Batman is a genius, a scientist, he works with what he can understand or prove, and during all his years fighting crimes, he saw two things: 1) the obvious one, he saw what happened in Metals, and us readers, all saw what happened in other realities such as Injustice: the death of the Joker brings chaos. It is his final plan, his killing joke, eather it is a nuke, a twisted Tim Drake or a Jokerized Batman. And since the Joker is unpredictible, even Batman doesn't know what would happen if he finally kills him.2) When Batman appeared in Gotham, he got rid of all the gangsters, Falcone, Maroni...the classics criminals. And what happened? They got replaced by freaks, lunatics, super criminals! Batman knows that there is some kind of tragic balance. That if he steps up and get rid of one criminal, an even bigger threat would appear to set things right. And since the Joker is the opposite of Batman on this balance, if he kills him, something would appear and destroy nearly everything in the good side of the balance in response. It is sad to say but that is why the Joker is not affraid to die, it is because he knows that what Batman is the most scared about is not him, but what would be the Joker's legacy if he kills him.

Message: Oh my fucking God. Somebody make him shut up! I swear to God this is the first time I wanted to throw Joker down a cliff exclusively for how obnoxious he is and that's saying something seeing how Joker is my favourite DC villain. I don't know what impression King has of him, but it's the typical stance of a writer that knows nothing about Joker and tries too hard to make him credible. Joker always has a method behind his madness even when he pretends otherwise. The Joker is a mask, he can be impulsive or gullible, but he's more controlled than he appears even when he was emotional and that didn't change for Prime earth Joker. He isn't unpredictable because he's impulsive, he's unpredictable because he thinks outside any conventional box. Here? He's just random for random's sake. It's not funny and it just makes him appear painfully idiotic. I sort of feel like reading a more unhinged version of Prime earth solo Harley, at least logic means little to her too and if stuff don't work in her delusion then just oops! Sounds familiar? Just lol. That or this is not my Joker and that time King posted a picture on his Twitter of an old golden age Batman cover with two Jokers on it was actually supposed to mean something. Overall, I just reject this Joker with every fiber of my being. The only moment that made me smile was him accidentally shooting the bride, but then he just goes on and on beating the same goddamn joke to death...and then Batman goes along with him. Maybe Batman should marry Joker if he loves him so much to indulge him like that. Problem solved.

Author: deathofink

Message: I don't even know what to say anymore. I'm not even angry at this point, I'm depressed.I think King's main issue is that in this comic at least he doesn't really focus on actual good story-telling, he focuses on expressing concepts. And that's fine sometimes, really, but it has been a constant emphasis mostly from The War of Jokes and Riddles and that gets tiring and it is unfortunately also limiting; it only allows for a game between dualities, an eternal dichotomy; even when King tries to make it more complex, it still remains easy. These characters aren't that simple.I can give some credit because this is probably one of those times we saw Joker in his most vulnerable and it's really actually really sad and pitiful, but it's depressing it had to be executed like this and the comic couldn't take its time, allow for some more subtlety, more thought-out dialogue, mostly when understanding Joker often requires to have a good eye for subtlety; he would never narrate his issues to the reader and if he does, then it's totally spontaneous or it has to be a person he feels really close to which till now it has only been Batman and Harley (not just Rebirth, but in general). But I also enjoyed the idea of Joker and Selina having some sort of friendship, because at the end of the day, the Batman villains are sort of in it together, despite the betrayals and the different goals, they just have a long history together, same as the heroes, but again, shame it was executed like this. It also rubbed me the wrong way that Batman had to be knocked out in such a ridiculous fashion only to allow Catwoman to shine by fighting Joker and there is really no good justification as to why Batman didn't try to trip Joker and just immobilize him before he could have the advantage, which adds another layer of uncaring attitude from King, almost as if everything that matters is the concept and how he gets there has little importance. But back to what I enjoyed, I also found it cute that Selina, while she did end up laughing that she won, she held Joker almost with tenderness; it implies that she's not quite done with her villain-side and remains attached to it, which can be another issue for her relationship with Batman, if we think about it. Or at least that's my interpretation. Again, odd though, that King entirely ignored the not so friendly encounter between Joker and Catwoman during Death of the family which, if I may add, entirely contradicts these two's feelings for eachother, with a Selina that feels mostly disgust for Joker and Joker who acted oddly and uncomfortably sexual towards her. I did expect at least a reference.Well, it could have been brilliant and since it wasn't, I'm mourning the waste of potential. No offense to those that already find this arc brilliant, but it's definitely something I can't get behind.

Message: This arc gives me mixed reactions. On one hand, I like seeing Bruce Wayne actually doing something important. Other than scenes with Selina at the festival or recounting wars in bed, we rarely se Bruce with his mask off outside of the cave. Also, it's good to see how Batman is coping with his falling out with Catwoman. However, Batman beating someone within an inch of their lives, because of a break up? Kind of pathetic. I actually enjoy when Batman's stony facade breaks and he goes overboard, but only when something insane happens like a Robin death. This kind of reaction to a break up just makes the character seem more like a crazy guy in a bat costume and less like a superhero. Also, his parents dying should not be compared to Selina leaving him. Ever.
Author: ofccoleblack

Message: " Batman beating someone within an inch of their lives, because of a break up? Kind of pathetic"I don't know if you've ever gotten through a bad break up with someone you loved very dearly, but a lot of people have killed themselves because of an event like that. Yeah it's not as physically brutal as watching your parents get gunned down, but it's a whole other different kind of emotional pain. You wonder why Batman, a guy who's gotten through the pain of having dead family members, would be so hurt over a break up? Because he's human. It hurts. He is a crazy guy in a bat costume. He's not really a superhero. On top of that, Batman was promised happiness and it was stripped away from him. That's another layer of pain for him.That's why I love the character. He's not better than us. Yes it is pathetic because that's what we're reduced to after break ups. In some ways, he's worse than most of us and I think that's also why people feel so attached and are able to relate with him more than any other superhero.

Message: I kinda get both sides of the whole "Batman beating someone within an inch of their lives, because of a break up? Kind of pathetic." Yes, it is pathetic that this is the first thing that comes to his mind after heartache. Go out and find some criminals to beat up instead of an actual punching bag. Or if he was that upset, go find Catwoman and question her since she's the source of all this pain. Speaking of which, yes, being Batman gives Bruce a unique layer of pain from this break up that we can't understand yet. It's not pathetic that he's in this much pain, or even that he's doing self-destructive things to "get over" it. It's sad, to me, that he goes out and acts like an emotionally unstable rookie and takes out his frustration on a criminal suspect. It's extremely short sighted for someone like him, who's always kept his instability in check with his intelligence.

Message: But he didn't, though, did he? He was doing what some people reading here expects of him, and he of himself, "be okay" after what happened. According to this issue, we see that he first found EVIDENCE, damning EVIDENCE that pointed him toward Freeze, and it seems that he just sorta lost control DURING the beat down. And AFTER the has CALMED down, he reexamined everything and came to the conclusion that he might have made a mistake, which lead to him TRYING TO FIX it as Bruce Wayne. If you read between the lines, he's trying to get Freeze out while at the same time investigating and catching the real culprit of the framing, which I'm guessing is Bane & co.And here's the thing about framing someone, if it doesn't work at all, it would be a pretty sh*tty job, wouldn't it? Message: Actually, it wouldn't be easy to find. The only evidence Batman has is the bullet and we didn't even see if it exited Nightwing's head. And if all you have is the bullet, there's no way to trace the origin. Barrel Groove wouldn't work because you don't have the original gun to compare it to. That method is used to narrow down suspects, not identify potential ones. Bullet Casing equipment wouldn't work since these bullets seem to be unaltered from being bought from a legal firearms salesman. At best, you could make guesses as to what gun shot it, but since it was purchased from a regular store and not the black market, it wouldn't be unique enough to actually trace to a specific location.

Message: In an article about gunshot wounds to the head, I read that 90% of the time, a bullet in the head is lethal. Oh and depression, because of the loss of her intellectual capacity.Cobblepot should be as much as a mess as Dick is. Even more, since Dick was said to have been extremely lucky, and also, since Penguin was shot. In the head. At point blank. By Jason. Freaking. Message: Well, thanks for asking. =)The thing is, I'm not so sure he is that out of character (or maybe Detective Comics is giving me a new perspective about out of character Batman as it can't be worst than that, can it?). He's grieving. He lost his chance at happiness, which already sent him spiraling. Then, he was still hurt, but Dick was there to do what he always does : make things lighter for him, so he doesn't feel crushed by his abandonment issues. But then, Dick was shot right in front his eyes. Now he almost lost Alfred, and there would have been nothing he could have done to prevent it. He keeps losing people, which is the worst thing that could happen to someone who, like I said, as abandonment issues. We saw back when Jason died, and again when Luthor momentarily killed Dick, and again when Damian died and again when Tim died... How unhinged that makes him. He gets more violent, less empathetic, less logical, because he feels guilt over the fact he can't protect the people he loves. The guilt becomes anger, so he starts pushing back everyone else, especially those who try to reason with him. This issue was good, IMO, because I could literally feel his anguish, his rage and his sense of unworthiness. When he hit Gordon, he hit himself. Because Gordon is being as blind as he was. He reminds him of his failure, when he refuses to believe him, the same way he refused to believe Cobblepot at the beginning. It's pretty intense, and, I think, absolutely heartbreaking. Bane is winning. The Bat is breaking.Now it's just my interpretation. I tried to detail my answer as much as I could, but I can understand if you don't share my views. It's very subjective. What's your take on the issue?

Message: So far some pretty negative comments, and I for one, as John might say, bloody love this issue, arc. Lemme tell you why, so nothing is as it seems. We have this story of young Bruce first, his youth, his struggles, which is pretty standard fare for Batman, but...it's not Bruce, it's Master Bruce, a villain. Then we have a deaf Batman chained up fighting Pyg, trying so hard to get away, but nothing seems to work, it's panic, it's fear, and it's disjointed and glitchy, and then...Pyg is Damian. At this point, it's pretty 'uh, wtf-town, population: us.' But it's this issue that clears it up some more. Bruce (real Bruce) is in a dream, Scarecrow gas is being used to drive him mad. So, let's take recontextualized look at parts one and two. Master Bruce going off killing people and having such a similar background to Regular Bruce is a fear he has. Is he a dark knight detective, protector of the innocent, or is he just one quick fall away from a raving mass murderer?  Then the Pyg one asks the same question, but instead of him, it's his son, who is/was a killer, depending on your definition. It isn't just about him anymore, it also is about his family, something which is lacking from a lot of 'deep dives into Bruce's brain' issues. Knowing this is nightmare stuff, it makes the whole 'being deaf and can't get away' thing make much more sense. Who hasn't had a nightmare like that? Where no matter how much you run, you can't get away? Then this one, is a lot more straight forward, as mentioned above. He fears for Catwoman's death, which again, is pretty standard, but he manifests John in his mind, not Superman or Dick Grayson. John could represent a lot of things, but I like to think of it as failure. It's what John's best at, or at least having pyrrhic victories. Batman yells at him about potential, but he's really talking to himself, because he knows 'Catwoman' is going to 'die' and he can nothing about it. He feels useless.My last point doesn't really tie so much into those previous points, but I think this issue has the penultimate dream, and the next one is when he snaps out of it, summons that second wind determination that we all know and love, and kicks some ass, Batman style. So, I think it's really telling about Bruce's headspace that he dreams of himself happy with Selina (despite the whole 'death' thing) rather than seeing his parents shot for the 16,463,645,1939 time.So, we might be in 'wtf-town' right now, but I think if King can nail the ending, this arc could be a classic.

Message: ... m'kay. I like Constantine (and generally speaking, it's always enjoyable to see him interacting with the Bat). I like Selina. I most definitely don't like Bruce. Not ever since #51, and especially RHATO #25. Nothing has happened ever since so that my liking towards him is restored.Oh, the artwork. The artwork is just lovely. I adore it.And all that said, I'm bored, guys. This is building up way too slowly. I don't like being teased in every single issue and then getting abolutely nothing as pay-off. It's not intriguing, it's tiresome. It's freaking dragging. I'm pretty sure all of those seemingly random issues will eventually be connected somehow, but I'm also pretty sure that it won't worth waiting... it's typical King writing. And I do like him as a writer in general, but he's terrible in handling cliffhangers, or giving us satisfying pay-offs.I normally vastly enjoy a good look into Bruce's psyche. I love action, but I'm not all about it. I love it when someone actually tries to go deep. But right now, I don't care about that! I want to see what the hell happens with Bane and freaking Thomas Wayne!! If you wanted me to care about those deep, artistic issues we've reccently got, King, well, you shouldn't have teased.

Message: I don't understand.It feels like this is trying to be clever.  There's clearly parallels being drawn between Coyote/Roadrunner and Batman/Joker.  But it doesn't make sense.  Is King trying to tell us that nothing's going to happen?   That the stakes here are meaningless and nothing will happen?We know that.  We figured it out at issue 50.  (and the particularly handsome among us discerned it a few issues after Alec started killing)  This series constantly drops massive cliffhangers and starts the next issue by mentioning "oh, everyone's fine" or just ignoring things altogether.  What good does pointing it out to the audience do?Is this a cry for help?  It wouldn't be the first time.  Bendis's USM run actually has a character beat the crap out of Peter and rant about how creatives have their ideas twisted by greedy fat cats. (irony!)  So at least there's precedent.  I can't think of a single other reason for a creator to actively draw attention to their story not doing anything.  Just drawing a blank.

Message: I wish we had seen more of the Bat-family and friends in that arc, because if Batman's worst nightmare is that he cannot love, at all, not just Selina (which is implied when Cat says that he forswore love when he chose war), then they're also concerned. It can seem a bit far-fetched that since he gives everything for his vow, his mission, it made him unable to love but I can get why Bruce would fear that. It's obvious that he has affection for people but it isn't not easy to everyone to know for sure if it's just that or if it is love. And emotionally speaking, Bruce is, well, he's Bruce.At the end of the day it all comes back to the same question, because it means his worst nightmare is that Selina was right to leave him because she was right that he cannot be Batman and be happy. And since he cannot stop to be Batman, that means that he'll have to live a miserable life. He'll have moments of joy, yes, but not happiness. His worst nightmare is that it is impossible for him to ever be truly happy, which is actually pretty human.I also liked the Bane/Thomas stuff. The whole "I'm messing up my sons's life so he stops being Batman and can have a happier life", that I had guessed, but it's surprising yet interesting how Thomas is having fun with Bane and that he has the last word in this issue.Still, I have one question: why is Bane always fighting NAKED?

Message: Yeah, I feel like King was sometimes just telling stories he wanted to tell regardless of how they fit in the whole nightmare thing. Like, he made a nightmare about Master Bruce only because he started 2018 with that character and wanted to end 2018 the same way. He made another Looney Tunes crossover only because the first one was quite popular and got him an award. I might be wrong though.As for the whole "he cannot be Batman and be happy", well, this issue tells us that's his worst nightmare, doesn't mean it is the truth. But maybe it's for the best that he and Selina didn't get married, because maybe he proposed to her because of that fear. See how when she tells him he doesn't love her, he answers "I have to"? So maybe he did the right thing for the wrong reason. Next time he proposes to her, it better be because he simply does loves her, not because he has to. And I think that's where we're heading, but I've been wrong before.

Message: He'd better not because the mistake of comics is their inability to retain development and use to propel the character forward to a status quo that makes them more refreshing. In this day and age the characters are no longer the same characters who were created to have no development whatsoever. The only one to my knowledge that retains such a character type are the ones over at Archie Comics and that is their greatest strength which keeps them out problems like having to adhere to continuity and reboots and retcons. Which is the mistake being committed over at Marvel as their new status quo is to have a Peter Parker who now hides behind the mask that's not refreshing at all. It makes him an even bigger loser than before. Also what off about what Mr. King's comments is how he describe Batman as a machine when he has been steadily portraying Batman as anything but a machine with him showing himself as vulnerable to things like emotion and even some how believed he would die. And if DC wants a true machine make characters based on Death Note's main characters all the smart guys save for Mello are machines.

Author: patitoconclase

Message: *reads the comments*everyone that said I was getting on about nothing for the Helena Wayne thing -- vindication. -_-I really enjoyed this, actually. It showed how new and inexperienced Bruce was, and for once the villains had a reason to interact with one another outside the usual 'let's take out the Bat!!!' scheme. I liked how Riddler's compulsion to solve a mystery is what led to all of this, that was really cool and overall I think everyone came out of this with a lot of good, solid history under their belts and some deep set motivations as well. Bruce is like any other human so it's only natural he'd be faced with that temptation to break the rule, to put down a monster who inflicted such suffering merely to satisfy his own arrogant curiosity. Makes sense. Joker making him who he is? No.More like, Joker reminded him of who he is. Tested him and he passed. Joker can't exist without Batman, we know that by now. If Batman killed, the game would be over. That's the point of the GAME. So it can only continue if he continues to 'stick to his code.' Joker had to push Batman that far -- it's the only way he could hurt Batman and still have the game preserved. This would establish their taunt/testing battles for years to come. It makes sense. I like it. This was a good arc.But WonderBat for life. *sulks*

Message: I've seen enough crazy reiterations of Scooby-Doo that a post-apocalypse setting wasn't too outrageous. Still, I agree with Rain Spectre, something about it just felt...off. The elements were all there.Personally, I feel that the mere fact that it was a survival post-apocalypse setting is what didn't make it work. Scooby-Soo is first and foremost a mystery. What if the post-apocalypse is already a given environment, and Mystery Incorporated have outfitted themselves to thrive in it? Perhaps they double as mystery solvers as well as monster hunters; maybe some of the mutants in this new world are very territorial, "haunting" various towns and communities based on the subconscious drives of their former human lives, or maybe there are malevolent humans who manipulate the mutants for their own gain. Perhaps there is a greater mystery to be solved within the series as to how the apocalypse even happened, which of course would tie back into what the series proper insinuated with Velma's profession, and Scooby being one of the many animal test subjects.

Message: I actually thought this was pretty decent. Going the comedic / light-hearted route with the Wonder Twins is probably a good idea, since trying to use them in a dark and gritty atmosphere probably wouldn't work. Besides, this is a nice change of pace from what superhero comics are typically like these days, i.e. grim and edgy soap operas that try to be "epic".Not to say that they shouldn't ever try to be serious. I think the ideal tone would be if they made it like the old Teen Titans cartoon. Not "Go!", the other one. That show would have Slade (and maybe a couple other villains) show up as an occasional serious threat, but the rest of the time it was mostly silly and light-hearted adventures. That's probably what this comic should go for.

Message: One may say this is what you expect after opening the Multiverse to the big unknown after Metal where many unknown things hit you all at once as consequence. But as a reader, so many big things happening and each going ''IT CAN BE THE END OF THE MULTIVERSE'', is just adding to the event fatigue that happens at Marvel too often. I hope DC doesn't follow suit with that.We have this Doom comet, just dealt with Omega Titans, Source Wall is leaking and can end everything in a year, there are Dark Gods 'wished' into existence from the Dark Multiverse...and so on.It is representative of the crazy nature of things after Metal opening a can of worms but again, as readers being overwhelmed, will not help the books.
Author: wowlock

Message: I can handle the craziness of DC Multiverse stuff, I could practically write a book on the subject. But this issue has us juggling a new League line-up, a complicated plot by Vandal Savage that we're just thrown into, J'onns backstory, the doom comet, and a dark secret that Vandal has. The fact that Luthor assassinates Vandal to gain a base for the new Legion of Doom is probably the simplest, most straightforward element of the plot, really. I think that we really should have held off on the doom-comet and other multiverse stuff until the second issue. Maybe tease it at the end of this one, but make the first issue primarily about showing us this new League's dynamic and letting us get used to the new tone. Throwing in everything at once just made things feel crowded.
Author: disqus_zPiyFYGk5g

Message: Kinda depressing to see this version of Lexor City. The name tickled something in the back of my brain so I googled it up. Lexor is from an old Silver Age story. Basically, Lex takes Superman to a world with a red sun and challenges him to a fair fight. Looser stays and the winner goes back to Earth. Superman wins and Luthor stays, eventually finding an inhabited, but ruined city. The people there were once incredibly advanced, but a war centuries prior had bombed their knowledge back to the stone age. Lex helps the people to understand their technology again and essentially creates a low-key utopia. After he leaves, the city is still grateful to him and build a massive statue of him and rename the city Lexor.

Message: That's increasingly true of most writers, I think it was Bendis or possibly Johns who has recently announced pompously that he doesn't intend to write about Superman, (or as little as he can get away with,) and will concentrate instead on Clark Kent; even though there's really no such person.Christopher Nolan's absolutely dire, The Dark Knight Rises, suffered from the exactly the same kind of creative arrogance; Batman was barely in it until right at the very end, at which point he was then effectively, "cured," of being Batman and wandered of to live happily ever after with Selena Kale who was similarly, "cured," of being Catwoman and what a pile of crap that was.Warren Ellis seems to be about the only major comic writer who can currently be bothered to commit the time, energy and attention to detail needed to write established characters well, his current run on The Wildstorm is absolutely exemplary even without their names and uniforms the key players and many of the supporting characters as well are still easily recognizable, (and he has a huge amount of fun with some brilliant misdirection,) even though many of them have been altered radically.That's how you do it, other writers please take note.

Message: Luthor: "If I found you here, Batman will be here in thirty minutes. Maybe fifteen." ... Seriously? Batman is a detective, fighter and engineer while Luthor is a businessman and scientist. Just being smarter by some IQ points does not mean you automatically gain skill equal or better that someone who honed it their whole life.To everyone commenting and tweeting "#Luthorwasright" and the like when he was monologuing to the Justice League, I would like to point out to you that he proclaims (wether truthfully or not, who can say) that he considers Joker to be a pinacle of humanity.Luthor makes super secret plans that Joker of all people hears about trough gossip despite everyone evading him like a plague when they have any choice in the matter, yet Justice League is caught completely unaware. No informants, no one cutting a deal with them, no one letting them know just because they would like to live longer and they think Luthor's plan would be the end of them or snitching just because Luthor did not involve them. Justice League is basically a form of law enforcement, yet we see no benefit that would bring. Lack of imagination on writers' part in my opinion.We finally get a competent villain. And while I like the double cross and the reasons for it, Joker is cranked up to eleven with his exact knowledge of what Luthor would do and his scientific and engineering and chemistry knowledge. Joker is great engineer, has some experience with poisons and science itself does not interest him. Even in this issue we are shown that he needs others to fine tune his grandiose plans and make sure his gas would not disipate between being released from balloon to descending on ground. He does not have expertise to design specific gas for each villain and make sure luthor is imune to all of them. He also despises letting others do bigger and badder things than he does, so him leaving Luthor to Freak-Who-Cackles feels really out of character for me. Which is a shame because as I said, I like his reasoning and intention to ruin the master plan just as it would be finishing.Neither villain is willing to face the fact the other is right. Joker always goes for a kill and Luthor always tries to be smarter than everyone and it got old long time ago. I like the fact that they are in character in the stubborn refusal to face the reality is what makes them villains, that Joker's murders are never going to have the effect he wants, Batman will not break and kill him because of it, and there will always be smarter people than Lex Luthor because no one knows everything and it takes time and effort to be expert in any given field.I do not like the art on Cheetah. It does not look all that bad, but... I don't know, looks more like an old lady than a humanoid feline.They kept Ivo's disfigurement. Nice. They are bringing back Brainiac. Bad. Very bad idea. And Lexyboy thinks he is so smart.I hope we get batman Who Laughs miniseries over quickly, I am sick and tired of that abomination running around DC.

Author: cicax

Message: Metal broke the Source Wall. No Justice introduced the world-eating Omega Titans. After discovering the doorknob at his dad's old Legion club, Luthor killed Vandal Savage and attempted to divert the earth's course away from the totality headed out from the Source Wall by breaking up the earth's crust. The JL thwarted that (by blowing up the moon?) and the totality landed. Superman and MM went in to investigate with Batman and Hawkgirl riding along, but they were hijacked by Luthor and Joker. Luthor had earlier put the Legion of Doom together to find the seven hidden energies and unlock the secret of the totality. To Luthor's dismay Hawkgirl reacted to the totality and a pattern emerged on her wings. She, MM and GL travelled to Thanagar Prime to find out more, but discovered that Shayera was holding the Martian Keep hostage in a machine that could create a facade of the Thanagar that had once been. Before she died, the Keep shared with J'onn a secret from his past that had apparently been wiped from his memory - the fact that he'd been abducted by humans as a child, who were researching how to make a human-Martian race for Perpetua (the goddess of the totality, creator of a universe before the current one.) Starman, a hero from the past with some connection to the Source Wall energy, discovered a way to use the remaining Omega Titans and Hawkgirl to repair the Source Wall. That ran into a snag when Brainiac and the Legion of Doom attacked and managed to raise Perpetua's body. But in this issue, they're still looking for a way to raise her mind.

Message: This was story telling perfection and I'm not even talking about the plot itself, but how Snyder tiptoes between the lines of established continuity. Never rewriting, but expanding, filling the cracks of previously left unclear or empty lore with fresh history and ultimately, in the DC-verse cosmic scale, changing none of the past accustomed plot-points but still presenting something new and exciting within the written universe's logic and natural laws.I'm not even a fan of the plot itself, but the amount of prep, research, and brainstorming Snyder has put into this book to create something new without shitting all over past writers' developments has earned a tremendous amount of respect from me. 10/10 kudos.

Message: multiple reasons.  To name a few... Its breathtakingly cynical, its filled with strawmen, the writing/art is nowhere near as trailblazing as everyone says it is.There are dozens of earlier series that I though contained greater imagination.  Art wise, compared with artwork by fellow wildstorm artists like Sean Phillips, Travis Charest and Lee Berjeemo, Hitch's art looks bland.I'd advise reading other series from around this time for comparison.  Even at just Wildstorm proper there was a large diversity of titles.   Ellis was just one creator among many.  But after his and Hitch's  Authority took off, the entire company just couldn't help but mirror it.  Worse, those few books that didn't had trouble existing in a shared universe with it.

Message: I'm starting to think that most of what's happening here is either going completely over your head or that you've been reading a completely different book to the one I've just read.There are a million brilliant little facets to this; such as Jenny, (who's already with Shen and is firmly established as being completely independent of both the IO and Skywatch,) telling Angie, "You seem like a good person, so we've got you're back," just a throwaway line; except that is exactly how the Authority always think.I think that both the IO and Skywatch are going to end up getting their arses kicked.Or the misdirection about Fairchild; her mum, (Alexandra,) has an evil Alien inside her, presumably her daughter, (Caitlin,) doesn't but will still have all her usual abilities; including her enormous.................IQ.To be fair to you, I'm old enough to have read all these characters as  Wild-storm tittles when they first came out and many of them were so utterly amazing that I can still remember much about them including the story lines, back plots and their context within the bigger Wild-storm picture as it where.Ellis also seems to have done something that too few writers really ever bother to do these days;  an enormous amount of fine and detailed research before he wrote this stuff, (far easier simply to retcon everything, re-imagine it or to present it as an another alternate version,) and it pay of in almost ever line of dialog, plot twist and panel, (the art is as good as plotting.)

Message: Warren Ellis has announced that his DC Comics series The Wild Storm will be taking a hiatus following October's #18, intending to work ahead so that the next arc - scheduled as the series' final arc - can run on a regular monthly schedule.	"The Wild Storm will take a two month break after issue 18 to get me and Jon Davis-Hunt some space to breathe for the last run from 19 to 24," Ellis wrote in his newsletter.	The Wild Storm's sister series, Michael Cray, is scheduled to end in October with #12.The planned Wildc.a.t.s. and Zealot series are still in development, with Ellis previously saying he had written the first issue of one. And having someone in DC universe have actual honest conversation about super-hero-ing and if it should be done before someone actually gets serious about it is something I waited for a long time. Message: Everyone's talking about feels, and yes, it was feelsy, but since I'm not gonna say the same things, I'd like to point out this is my favorite type of Batman story.So, a lot of times writer's like to get angsty with Batman and put him in a more realistic world and throw politics in, and what I mean by that is 'Batman makes his own enemies! He's bad for Gotham! If he stopped Gotham would be great! Therefore Batman is actually Bad-man!'That is bullshit.What I like about this is that Gotham is a place where bad things are going to happen, and when bad things happen, there's a man out there who will fight it, even if it means getting stabbed, shot, beaten up, scarred, hated, feared. He does it anyway, because he has to. That's Batman to me.

Everything about this just screams last minute rush job, and it also makes Peter look like the biggest sucker in the world.  If I were him, I would've told her to go take a flying leap.However, that brings me to another point.  There is the potential that this could lead to something redeeming and long overdue.  We've seen from the previews for next issue that they'll be getting quite intimate but she'll push him away again when she sees the spider suit.  Well I'm hoping it'll lead to Peter finally telling her, "Y'know what MJ, I've had it with this crap!" and then goes off on her about how unfair she's been towards him these past few years.  But considering that Slott's Peter Parker is more whipped than the Smallville version of Clark Kent, I really don't see that happening sadly.

Message: I think Superior Spider-Man was overall pretty underwhelming. It started great, it was a very good idea, but it went south really fast mainly because of the way Otto was written and the way the story escalated to absurd levels really fast. I mean... when the comic ended Spider-Man was kind of an evil genious who had monitored the entirety of New York city, had his own army, his own mechas and an evil lair (and killed people), and no one ever seemed to care or think anything was wrong or different about him (not enough to confront him at least). It got so ridiculously over the top that it didn't work. But that doesn't make this plot twist any less effective or this particular issue any worse.This was a great 700th issue regardless of what happened next.And to everyone who thinks this "destroyed Peter Parker" somehow (who reading this comment section are apparently some people) I have this to say; No, it didn't. It didn't destroy anything. Just like Peter wasn't destroyed after OMD, or how he wasn't destroyed after the Ben Reilly affair in the 90's, or that one time he stopped being a radioactive hero and his origin was retold so he's the avatar of some spider-god or some shit like that (remember that? That's probably Spider-Man's biggest retcon and no one seems to go apeshit about it ever!). And it didn't simply because this is a character that has existed for 52 years. This is a character that has been written by more writers that anyone can name, who has been through more changes in his status quo that anybody can mention. And that's the whole point of comics, a writter comes and does whatever he/she wants with the character. Because, aside from the somewhat predefined personality (like you can't make a brooding, dark, edgy Peter Parker or an easy going jokester Batman -unless it doesn't last and the change has an explanation plotwise) there's nothing fixed. What happens to them, the adventures they live, their status quo... are kind of irrelevant. They're just background noise.This, like any other change in Spider-Man's history, made a number of changes, some lasted, some (most in this particular case) didn't. Just like any other time a writer (or the editors at Marvel) tried to do something "new and original" with the character. Because that's how comic books work. And sure, as fans we all will have nostalgia towards our favourite period of time of our favourite superhero character(s) but that doesn't mean they have to stay that way (whatever "that way" is) forever. If that was true then Peter would still be a teenager going to high school. And nobody really wants that.
Author: disqus_zeEKpNxImG

Message: I actually loved this story. The stakes were high and the writing was excellent. The build up really makes me feel like Peter is going to claim his life back and triumph as usual, but no. It really made you feel something, even if you knew Peter would come back eventually.The character development along this run from Ock was phenomenal, and I can't lie, the people who hated this story most likely hated it simply because they don't like Dan Slott and have a massive bias against him, as well as those who don't like change and always force marvel to bring stuff back to the way they were before. This story was a massive risk and paid off, and I for one am glad he did it
